 :tx/rationale "Create task: SOUND-CRASH: Crash-recovery test for LiveStore. CONTEXT: LiveStore claims crash safety via append-only EDN txn files with fsync. Architecture: write_tx() writes EDN with fsync then applies in-memory; flush() serializes store.bin; on next open, recovery replays txn files not in store.bin. This design is sound but NEVER TESTED. No test simulates crash mid-write. No test verifies corrupt txn file handling. No test verifies store.bin + txn files = txn files alone (store.bin is optimization, not source of truth). Multi-writer race on store.bin also untested. RATIONALE: Crash safety is a foundational claim that justifies the entire persistence architecture. An untested claim is an unverified claim. One test can verify the invariant that txn files are the source of truth. APPROACH: (1) test_crash_recovery_store_bin_deletion: write N txns via LiveStore, flush, delete store.bin, reopen — verify store.datoms() == original. This proves txn files alone are sufficient. (2) test_crash_recovery_partial_txn: write N txns, append truncated bytes to a new txn file (simulating partial write), reopen — verify graceful error handling or skip of corrupt file, and that valid txns are preserved. (3) test_multi_writer_convergence: open two LiveStore instances on same .braid dir, write different txns from each, flush both, reopen fresh — verify combined store has all txns from both writers. (4) test_store_bin_is_optimization: write N txns, verify store after open-with-store.bin == store after open-without-store.bin (datom-by-datom equality). ACCEPTANCE: (A) All 4 tests pass. (B) test_crash_recovery_store_bin_deletion proves txn files are source of truth. (C) Corrupt txn file is handled without panic (either skip with warning or error with recovery path). (D) Multi-writer test shows no data loss. FILE: crates/braid/src/live_store.rs (test module) or tests/crash_recovery.rs (integration test). TRACES-TO: INV-STORE-009 (frontier durably stored), INV-STORE-020 (store.bin = fold(txn_files))."
